{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646395"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:29:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:29:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18177"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18177","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18177"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10891"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79235"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10891"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18177"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64577"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25327"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25330"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27126"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79235"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe back muscles are divided into three layers, these being the superficial, intermediate, and deep.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is classified as a deep muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Iliocostalis","Latissimus dorsi","Longissimus","Semispinalis","Spinalis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esemispinalis\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is part of the deep layer of the intrinsic back muscles. It is involved in extending and rotating the vertebral column.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIliocostalis\u003C/strong\u003E - Part of the erector spinae group, which is considered intermediate in depth\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELongissimus\u003C/strong\u003E - Also part of the erector spinae group, intermediate in depth\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpinalis\u003C/strong\u003E - Another muscle of the erector spinae group, intermediate in depth\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELatissimus dorsi\u003C/strong\u003E - A superficial muscle of the back, not part of the intrinsic back muscles\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The semispinalis muscle is part of the deep layer of the intrinsic back muscles.","The deep muscles of the back are responsible for movements and stabilization of the vertebral column.","The erector spinae group, which includes iliocostalis, longissimus, and spinalis, is considered part of the intermediate layer of intrinsic back muscles."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood, C. A., Wirth, M. A., \u0026 Fehringer, E. V. (2016). Rockwood and Matsen\u0027s The Shoulder E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","DeSai C, Reddy V, Agarwal A. Anatomy, Back, Vertebral Column. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.ni